# Refactoring (Orbit Wars)

Adapted from [cursorrules-collection `practices/refactoring.mdc`](https://github.com/nedcodes-ok/cursorrules-collection/blob/main/rules-mdc/practices/refactoring.mdc).

## Before you change behavior

- Targeted tests first: `make test-fast` or `make test-domain-{config,features,policy,artifacts,curriculum}` for the touched area.
- Do not run slow/jax/sweep smokes during iteration unless the user asks.
- One logical refactor per change set — no feature + rename + reformat in one diff.

## Project-specific

- **Unified v2 only:** feature path is `encode_turn` → `TurnBatch`; remove v1 paths and compatibility re-exports — update call sites.
- **No parallel APIs** for moves/renames; no `_underscore` alias modules.
- **Hydra:** edit `conf/` groups + `src/config/schema.py`; verify with `uv run ow train print_resolved_config=true`.
- **CLI:** new capabilities go in `src/cli/<module>.py` + `src/cli/__init__.py`, not `scripts/*.py`.

## Technique

- Guard clauses / early returns; max ~3 indentation levels in Python control flow.
- Extract when a block needs a comment to explain *what*; keep helpers in the owning package (`src/jax/rollout/`, not a grab-bag util).
- Smallest step → run targeted tests → next step.

## Anti-patterns

- Refactor without tests on the code path.
- “Cleanup” that adds shims or dual encoding/rollout paths.
- Large cross-cutting renames in the same diff as behavior changes.
- Editing `docs/architecture/` diagrams only when the pipeline boundary actually moved.

**Note:** Test each step; commit only when the user asks (not every refactor step).
